s previously thought. Healy’s study examines the archaeological record of one subarea of Southern Central America, the Rivas region of Pacific Nicaragua. The work gives a detailed analysis of excavations and of artifacts recovered at seven significant prehistoric sites. A critical pioneering effort, the monograph documents cultural changes occurring over a 2,000–year time period—changes in technology, material culture, settlement, subsistence, and socio–political organization.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aExcavations (Archaeology)zNicaraguaxRivas (Department). 0aPotteryzNicaraguaxRivas (Department). 4aSocial Science: Archaeology. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / Central America.2bisacsh1 aHealy, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPohl, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920784440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889207844423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889207844/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles